<TEXT>
us defense secretary frank carlucci and japanese 
officials have discussed washingtons plans to develop a jet 
fighter known as the fsx a carlucci aide said friday 
he also said carlucci is very pleaced with americanjapanese 
defense cooperation including sharing the costs of maintaining us 
servicemen in japan 
the aide a senior defense department official spoke with the 
condition he not be indentified 
carlucci held two days of talks with senior japanese defense and 
foreign ministry officials and there were no areas of significant 
disagreement according to the official 
carlucci arrived in tokyo thursday to brief japanese authorities 
on the ussoviet summit conference in moscow and discuss 
bilateral issues 
the aide said carlucci and japanese defense officials discussed 
only in general terms the plans to jointly develop the fsx fighter 
however this works out it will be in a positive way he 
said it is a signpost for the future for both of us because an 
essential part of our defense relationship will be the exchange of 
technology a twoway flow 
the japan broadcasting corp a public television network said 
the two sides agreed to set up a technology steering committee 
to oversee the transfer of fsx technology between the japanese 
defense agency and the us air force 
it said the 13 billion needed for developing the jet fighter 
will come from japanese firms with us companies as 
subcontractors and the united states will develop the planes 
engines and japan its radar system 
carluccis aide said both countries are constantly 
addressing the issue of financial support for the more than 
50000 american military personnel stationed in the main japanese 
islands and okinawa 
some us congressmen have said japan should do more because of 
the enormous increase in the value of the yen which has more than 
doubled against the dollar in the last three years 
were not going around with a tin cup because we need help 
with our budget problems the aide said you cant go around 
poormouthing your friends they get tired of it 
when you talk about burdensharing we should talk about 
mutual security and joint cooperation and identify areas of 
weakness 
japan provides more than 45000 worth of support annually for 
each us serviceman stationed here assistant defense secretary 
richard l armitage told congress march 17 it also helps pay some 
expenses of the 21000 japanese working at us bases 
altogether japan will spend 25 billion the most 
generous hostnation support arrangement the us enjoys anywhere 
in the world armitage said 
