divers have discovered 55 japanese warships 
cargo boats and submarines sunk during world war ii off palau in 
the western pacific ocean the government announced 
no one knew they were there government spokesman bonifacio 
basilius said friday 
elderly palauans believe the vessels were part of the japanese 
fleet used to protect the philippines that had moved to malakal 
harbor off koror palaus capital basilius said 
japanese ships anchored at malakal and airai harbor were 
attacked by us carrierbased fighter planes in march and july 
1944 he said 
japan occupied palau which is about 600 miles east of the 
philippines and nearly 2000 miles south of tokyo from 1922 until 
american forces captured the island chain in 1945 
the ships were found during the past four weeks by us navy 
reservists on summer duty from honolulu long beach calif san 
diego and texas basilius said 
the us national park service has been locating and marking 
sunken ships the spokesman said the joint park servicenavy 
project is expected to end in two weeks 
most of the search has been in and around palaus rock islands 
which are limestone coral reefs with a mushroomlike appearance 
created by wave erosion none are inhabited 
the divers are using underwater robots with cameras basilius 
said none of the ships were visible from the ocean surface and 
some have been found in waters 150 feet deep most were less than 
five miles from shore 
divers were able to read the names on five of the ships which 
they described as in good shape for being under water for more than 
40 years basilius said the warships seemed to be destroyers 
palauans have known about a dozen other sunken japanese ships 
basilius said 
