<TEXT>
a state jury cleared a blood bank of liability in 
the aids infection of a woman who received a tainted transfusion 
and a defense attorney said it was a victory for blood banks facing 
similar lawsuits 
the denver district court jury on friday found united blood 
services not liable for damages in the case of susie quintana 50 
of dolores who contracted aids from a 1983 transfusion after an 
accidental gunshot wound the blood was from the united blood 
services bank in albuquerque nm 
the sixmember jury thursday ordered an infectious disease 
expert whose aids test falsely found mrs quintana free of the 
virus to pay 70000 in damages but found no liability on the part 
of her former family doctor 
lawyers have said the case may be the first in the nation in 
which a jury decided an aids victims claim against a blood bank 
in a similar case in california in 1986 a settlement was reached 
before the trial ended 
there are many lawsuits and they the jurors have done a 
great service to blood banks around the country defense attorney 
steve labensky said after the verdict defense attorneys around 
the country were watching this a victory here will probably assure 
a victory elsewhere 
wiping tears from her eyes mrs quintana said she knew the jury 
faced a tough decision in her case but it means aids 
patients will just have to keep fighting said the mother of 
four ive fought this thing every since i found out i had it 
and ill continue to fight it 
mrs quintana and her 53yearold husband chris have not 
decided whether to appeal said their attorney maureen reidy witt 
the southwest colorado couples suit sought unspecified damages 
but witt asked the jury in closing arguments to award quintanas 
more than 13 million 
the jury said the infectious disease expert dr donald kearns 
was liable because he failed to explain precautions the couple 
should have taken to avoid exposing mrs quintanas husband to 
acquired immune deficiency syndrome 
although the quintanas testified they had sex after the tests 
quintana has tested negative for the aids virus 
dr edward g merritt the former family physician was also 
accused of failing to diagnose the virus and not recommending 
precautions but was found not liable 
the couples lawsuit named the blood bank kearns and merritt 
the quintanas did not sue southwest memorial hospital in cortez 
where mrs quintana received the transfusion 
in closing arguments witt said the blood bank was negligent for 
failing to properly screen donors and test its blood supply 
she said testing routinely used at the time to detect the 
hepatitisb virus in blood could have been useful in eliminating 
homosexual blood donors who are at high risk for that disease as 
well as aids 
douglas irish an attorney for the blood bank said tests for 
aids in blood were not available until two years after mrs 
quintanas transfusion 
labensky said his client felt what they were doing was 
reasonably prudent at the time and apparently the jurors agreed 
jurors said they had difficulty deciding what aids screening 
standards were at the time and whether the blood bank lived up to 
them 
three of us felt they met the industrys requirements and 
three did not said foreman albert gonzales i was surprised we 
came up with an answer 
while there was tremendous sympathy for mrs quintana and her 
family we had to set that aside and look at the evidence 
aids breaks down the bodys immune system leaving victims 
susceptible to infections and cancer 
it is spread most often through sexual contact needles or 
syringes shared by drug abusers infected blood or blood products 
and from pregnant women to their offspring 
