a federal appeals court has affirmed the right 
of death row inmates to legal aid in what lawyers say is the first 
ruling of its kind in the nation though most states already 
guarantee such aid 
obviously were very pleased richmond attorney gerald 
zerkin said friday it resolves a very difficult situation in 
which men on death row did not have access to counsel to challenge 
their death sentences 
the ruling by the 4th us circuit court of appeals upheld a 
1986 decision by us district judge robert r merhige jr that 
decision had been overturned last year by a threejudge panel of 
the appeals court 
fridays 64 ruling means that virginia will have to provide 
legal counsel for death row inmates who request representation for 
their appeals zerkin said he said the specifics of how 
representation will be provided remain to be worked out 
jonathan sasser a durham nc attorney involved in the case 
said the ruling gives impoverished death row prisoners access to 
the courts 
for a death row inmate in virginia it means you have to have 
a living breathing attorney to represent you he said from his 
durham office 
virginia law provides no guarantee of legal assistance once an 
inmates sentence has been affirmed by the state supreme court 
the 11page ruling is the first decision of its kind zerkin 
said but he added that it is grounded in the particular facts of 
virginias death row 
many i would say most states already provide representation 
without having been required to do so zerkin said 
the case was brought to federal court in 1986 by death row 
inmate joseph giarratano who was disturbed by the case of earl 
washington another death row inmate who could not afford a lawyer 
no volunteers could be found to handle washingtons case until 
about a week before his execution date when he won a stay his 
appeals are still continuing 
he was sitting there waiting to be executed and he couldnt do 
anything about it because he didnt have an attorney sasser 
said the importance of this case is that that wont happen 
again unless the supreme court reverses it 
