<TEXT>
six miners were pulled alive from a 
mine shaft today three days after an explosion trapped them in a 
pocket of air deep underground rescuers who had given up hope 
said there may be more survivors 
its a miracle said petercarl ruehland a spokesman for 
preussen elektra the company that owns the mine the rescue came 
with the help of a television crews microphone that picked up 
tapping sounds 
in all 57 miners were trapped in wednesdays explosion at the 
stolzenbach coal mine as of early today 15 men were still missing 
and 36 had been confirmed dead 
the dramatic rescue sparked hopes for finding more survivors 
officials said there were some indications that two more men may be 
near the pocket of air more than 300 feet underground where the six 
spent 65 hours 
its a faint hope but a supervisor said there were tracks of 
two people who may also be in an area where they may have 
survived said heinz cramer a board member of preussen elektra 
were stepping up the search 
he said about 200 workers were involved in the search in the town 
of borken 72 miles northeast of frankfurt 
rescue workers some with tears in their eyes broke into 
applause as the exhausted but otherwise unhurt survivors were 
brought to the surface in a special cage that had been lowered into 
a shaft by a crane 
where is my ahmet where is my little ahmet were the first 
words of supervisor thomas gepperth as he emerged 
he was asking about ahmet batkan a turkish immigrant worker who 
was lifted out before him 
gepperth who led the turk and the five germans men to safety 
was the only one to walk rather than be carried on a stretcher 
everybody was making their last wills and testaments 
gepperth said i told them they didnt have to 
gepperth was interviewed by hesse state television as he strode 
to join his men his brief remarks taped early today were 
broadcast later in the day 
family members rushed to embrace the men whose blackened faces 
showed fatigue they were put on stretchers and carried to a nearby 
rescue station in the mine 
as they were led in an ambulance to be examined by doctors at a 
nearby hospitals the miners waved and smiled wearily officials 
said all six were later released and allowed to go home 
the six men were found in a deadend tunnel about 330 feet long 
10 feet wide and 8 feet high 
cramer said that when the group felt the shock wave of the blast 
wednesday they ran toward an exit but gepperth a veteran 
36yearold miner and a trained rescuer realized they were running 
into high concentrations of deadly carbon monoxide when he saw 
another man stagger and run out of strength 
gepperth then turned the group in the other direction and 
instructed them to be as calm as possible to conserve oxygen cramer 
said 
to the right and to the left of where they were the levels of 
carbon monoxide were rising ruehland said 
the rescue came early today after work crews drilled an air shaft 
in the north section of the mine where officials believed most of 
the remaining men were trapped 
the rescuers planned to release carbon monoxide to facilitate the 
search and were surprised when oxygen came out instead 
a cord was extended to 230 feet and a microphone was carefully 
lowered in by rescue workers it picked up distinct regular tapping 
sounds 
the microphone also picked up voices for a brief period but they 
later disappeared according to a description provided by hesse 
state radio and television 
after more than three hours of digging the rescue workers broke 
into the air pocket and found the men 
