india may soon begin withdrawing some 
of the 50000 troops it sent to sri lanka over the past 10 months to 
enforce an indianbrokered peace accord press reports said saturday 
the united news of india quoted officials at the indian high 
commission or embassy in colombo as saying the withdrawal of the 
troops could begin as early as tuesday it did not identify the 
officials 
a report to be published sunday in the governmentowned sunday 
observer newspaper and made available to the associated press said 
the indian armys tank and artillery units will be withdrawn this 
week 
an independent sinhalese newspaper the sunday divaniya said 
that as many as 8000 indian troops may be pulled back from sri 
lanka starting early next week 
but nirupam sen deputy indian high commissioner in colombo told 
the ap that no time has been set for a pullout 
some equipment and troops that are not necessary will be sent 
back but we are still finalizing the exact time said sen 
indian defense minister kc pant told reporters during a visit 
tuesday that indian forces will begin withdrawing in the near 
future but he gave no specific date 
indian began sending troops to sri lanka on july 30 a day after 
indian prime minister rajiv gandhi and sri lankan president junius 
r jayewardene signed a peace accord aimed at ending a fiveyear 
insurgency by the islands minority tamils 
india is the dominant power in the region and its 60 million 
ethnic tamils are sympathetic to their sri lankan brethren 
tamils who are mostly hindus make up 18 percent of sri lankas 
16 million population they claim they are discriminated against by 
the majority sinhalese buddhists who control the government and 
military 
militant tamils have waged a guerrilla war since 1983 for more 
political autonomy or an independent homeland in the north and east 
of the island where most tamils live 
the accord called for the tamil rebels to lay down their arms in 
exchange for political concessions such as the creation of district 
councils with control over education law enforcement and land 
distribution all now handled by the federal government 
but the liberation tigers of tamil eelam the largest and most 
extreme of the rebel groups rejected the pact 
india which initially sent about 6000 troops to the island 
increased its manpower and launched a major offensive against the 
tigers last october to drive them out of the northern jaffna 
peninsula since may 23 the indian forces have been conducting 
searchanddestroy missions against tiger bases around the eastern 
port town of mullaitivu 
indian officials have said that 36 tamil rebels and 10 indian 
soldiers have been killed in the latest fighting india said friday 
that 18 indian soldiers also died when a mine exploded under their 
truck earlier in the week just west of the battle area 
at least 480 indian soldiers have died during the 10 months the 
troops have been on the island no official figures are available on 
tamil rebel deaths but unofficial estimates have put them over 
1000 more than 8000 people are believed to have died since the 
tamil insurgency began 
