<TEXT>
the soviet union made significant 
improvements in human rights in the past half year though the 
wellpublicized drive for freedom faltered on some fronts the state 
department said saturday in a major report to congress 
the department criticized what it called a crackdown on 
demonstrations complained that rights activists telephones were 
disconnected and said the governmentcontrolled press wrote 
distorted accounts of the protests 
rights performance in poland east germany romania and other 
east bloc countries was also a mixed bag of oldstyle repression and 
new progress according to the 137page document 
before being made public the report was distributed to members 
of congress friday as president reagan returned from the moscow 
summit but dissemination apparently was timed to meet a june 3 
deadline set by legislation calling for the report not to add 
substance to the human rights concerns expressed by reagan during 
his week of summitry 
after the united states signed the 1975 rights pact at the 
conference on security and cooperation in europe congress asked the 
department to report twice a year on whether the eastern europeans 
were complying with the bargain 
the result until soviet leader mikhail gorbachev arrived on the 
scene in 1985 has been a pile of reports filled with detailed 
distressing evaluations of the human condition in eastern europe 
including accusations of widespread failure to comply with pledges 
to grant freedom of assembly religion speech association 
emigration and travel 
the latest survey covering the six month period after oct 1 
1987 said although many aspects of soviet and east european 
implementation of csce commitments in the areas of human rights and 
economic cooperation remain seriously flawed there have been 
significant improvements in a number of areas 
on the positive side were increased emigration the release of 
some prisoners from labor camps relaxed rules on travel abroad by 
soviet citizens and best of all the report said the continued 
tolerance of unofficial groups and new freedom to publish tracts 
ranging from criticism of the government to george orwells animal 
farm 
the limits of what was permissible to print continued to 
expand and public discussion of problems became more frank the 
report said 
on the negative side soviet performance in the field of human 
rights deteriorated in some areas compared to the last reporting 
period the report said 
between 250 and 450 political or religious prisoners remain in 
jail and restrictions on religion continue 
the most detailed criticism touched on soviet handling of public 
protests 
the authorities cracked down on demonstrations taking 
extraordinary measures to prevent them or stop them as soon as they 
started the report said in another apparent retreat from 
previous progress soviet authorities disconnected the telephones of 
some human rights activists and selectively interfered with 
telephone service in order to prevent undesired conversations 
here are some highlights of the reports on other eastern european 
countries 
romania all freedoms remain sharply limited including 
romanias particular discrimination against ethnic minorities an 
amnesty declared by president nicolae ceausescu to honor his 70th 
birthday resulted in the release of an unprecedented number of 
prisoners 
poland the government continues to permit a relatively free 
intellectual life but during the reporting period authorities 
banned an independent discussion club in gdansk and harassed 
participants in independent political and union activities 
hungary the country continued to hold a reputation for being 
the least repressive of the warsaw pact countries an increase in 
contact between senior western visitors and the hungarian opposition 
was a notably positive development during the reporting period 
east germany all rights are limited but progress was seen in 
the increase of travel rights in allowed importation of some 
foreign literature and in a slight indication of better 
churchstate communication 
czechoslovakia the report on this country was as gloomy as 
ever repression of a march 25 civil rights demonstration in 
bratislava was the most serious known example of abuse 
bulgaria it remained a tightly controlled society despite an 
agreement with turkey to discuss human rights problems there 
appears to be no letup in discrimination against the turkish 
minority in bulgaria 
