some 5200 persons may have been exposed to 
hepatitis a last month because a worker at a fastfood restaurant 
unknowingly had the liver disease health officials said 
health officials said that the unidentified worker at a wendys 
restaurant on pacific highway in south seattle was diagnosed as 
having the disease friday 
as a precaution patrons were urged to get an injection of immune 
globulin which contains antibodies to the virus and could forestall 
the illness if they had eaten at the restaurant recently 
those who had eaten there more than two weeks earlier would not 
benefit from the injections because immune globulin must be 
received no later than 14 days after exposure to be effective said 
lois schipper nurse epidemiologist for the seattleking county 
health department 
officials estimated the number of people who could have eaten at 
the restaurant during the times the worker was there at 5200 
hepatitis is an inflammation of the liver that can range from 
mild to lifethreatening hepatitis a is caused by a virus that can 
be passed by an infected person touching food with unclean hands or 
through food or water contaminated with fecal material 
symptoms include fever nausea vomiting loss of appetite 
fatigue sore muscles dark urine lightcolored stools and yellow 
skin or eyes the incubation period is two weeks to six weeks 
the wendys restaurant worker is the latest of more than 75 food 
handlers diagnosed with the disease during the past three years in 
the puget sound area where there has been a hepatitis epidemic 
