traditionally the japanese have looked at platinum the way 
the rest of the world looks at gold said richard levine vice 
president of elders futures incs precious metals and foreign 
exchange group 
wedding rings in japan are made of platinum not gold he 
said for one reason or another platinum always was a desired 
metal in japan 
johnson matthey noted a huge increase in japanese purchases of 
platinum in the last two months of 1987 as us investors spooked 
by the stockmarket crash moved their money out of precious metals 
and into lessrisky investments such as government securities 
japanese buying continued apace as the selloff of precious 
metals in the united states sent platinum prices plunging below 
460 an ounce in february when platinum futures actually traded at 
a discount to gold analysts said 
new japanese tax laws making precious metals more appealing than 
savings accounts to investors also encouraged japanese buying of 
platinum experts agree 
back in the united states the calamity that many economists had 
predicted last fall failed to materialize instead the economy 
appears to be picking up steam which combined with sharp 
increases in agricultural commodity prices has been interpreted as 
a harbinger of rising inflation 
the inflation fears have renewed interest in precious metals 
among us investors who traditionally see gold silver and 
platinum as safe havens against rising prices 
i think investors got tired of earning 7 percent or 8 percent 
on their riskless investments particularly when they think 
inflation is picking up and theyre taking on a little bit of a 
more speculative bent said jacques luben executive director of 
investments for the new yorkbased platinum guild international 
analysts said the return of us investors to the precious 
metals has supported the entire complex but platinum has responded 
most sharply because of the already strong demand from the far east 
in addition the economys unexpectedly strong showing suggests 
growth in industrial demand for platinum which is used in 
automobile pollutioncontrol devices 
the possibility that south africa may halt platinum shipments to 
the united states if congress approves tougher trade sanctions also 
has underpinned platinums gains but most analysts say the threat 
is very remote 
the platinum market much thinner than the gold market is 
inherently volatile and some analysts warn that platinums gains 
may be overdone 
the very fact that the market has even focused on south africa 
indicates the market is taking the most bullish stance it could 
possibly take said george anagnos metals analyst for thomson 
mckinnon securities inc in new york 
some price increase is justified he said but unless this 
bullish interpretation pans out in every respect were going to be 
very vulnerable 
</TEXT>
